                    SCD command notation 1

  <exp> <address>

  Address can be an expression that specifies
  an address at the assembler level.

   Available operators
	+	Addition
	-	Subtraction
	*	Multiplication
	/	Division
	%	Remainder
	&	Logical AND
	|	Logical OR
	!	Logical negation
	^	Exclusive OR

                    SCD command notation 2

   Address expressions that can be used

    03c3            (Hexadecimal)
    \123            (Decimal)
    _1100011        (Binary)
    .symbol         (Assembler symbol names)
    .23             (Source line number addressing)
    ..filename.12   (Address by filename and line number)
                     The extension is omitted.
  <size>
   size   :   s(byte) w(word) l(long) Either
              If <size> is omitted, it is considered to be word.

  <range>
   range  :   <start_address> <end_address>
              or
              <start_address> L<length_byte>

                    C language expression notation 1

<Cexp>
It is written in the same format as expressions in C language.
Example:
    123         (Decimal)
    0x6a000     (Hexadecimal)
    i           (Variable i)
    *p          (The memory contents pointed to by pointer p)
   The scope (visibility) of a variable depends
   on the program counter currently being traced.
   In other words, in order of priority,
   - Variables declared within the current block
   - Variables declared within the current function
   - Static variables declared in the current module
   - Globally declared variables
It will be searched in the following order.
If the current program counter does not belong to any function,
or if the frame pointer is not set at the beginning of
a function entry, only global variables can be referenced.

                    C language expression notation 2

Most types and operators that can be expressed in C
are supported, with the exception of the ternary operator (?:)
and complex cast operators, which cannot be used.
If you want to change the value of a variable,
write an assignment expression. (variable name = value)
Even in other cases, if you write an operator that causes
side effects (such as assignment, increment, decrement, or
function call) in an expression, side effects will occur.
  <format>
   format specifies the format for displaying C expressions
   using one of the following characters.
	  	s  :String
		c  :Character
		x  :Hexadecimal
If format is omitted, the value of the expression
is normally displayed in decimal.
Example:    -? argv[0];s
            Displays the value of argv[0] in string format.

                    Coprocessor Control Commands

XFPCP :FPCP on<>off (/f)
XDIS  :Change source window floating point representation (/d)
XFX   :Change register window floating point representation (/d)
XFP   :Floating point register display on<>off (/x)

Floating-point coprocessor instructions are not available unless
the optional 68882 floating-point coprocessor is installed.
No operations are allowed on floating point values.

All that is allowed is to evaluate floating-point expressions
using C expressions and put the results
in registers or assembler.
In addition, string conversion functions such as
the ECVT function have side effects on their own buffers,
and simply evaluating an expression with the ? command
can change the flow of a program.
The display in parentheses is the option setting
at the time of operation.

                    Command option settings

/b<Palette code>   :Background color specification
/c<Memory size>    :Memory size to give to child processes
/d                 :Register window and register window
                    floating-point representation (XDIS and XFX) 
/f                 :Enable FPCP (XFPCP)
/i<Tab size>       :Set tab size (2=default)
/j                 :Start in Japanese
/p<Palette code>   :Pen color specification
/r                 :Remote Console Mode
/t                 :Start in console mode
/x                 :Floating-point register display (XFP)

Options can also be specified in the configuration file
(SCD.CNF).
